ROCKY MOUNTAIN SPOTTED FEVER - BRAZIL (03): (SAO PAULO)
*******************************************************
A ProMED-mail post
http://www.promedmail.org
ProMED-mail is a program of the
International Society for Infectious Diseases
http://www.isid.org

Date: Sat 29 Sep 2012
Source: TV Claret [in Portuguese, trans. Mod.JW, edited]
http://www.tvclaret.com/noticias/saude%20e%20ciencia/31259/PIRACICABA+REGISTRA+TRES+CASOS+DE+FEBRE+MACULOSA


Epidemiological surveillance confirmed 3 cases of spotted fever in Piracicaba city and is still studying 4 suspected cases.

In all, in 2012 alone, another 18 suspected cases have been registered in the Municipal Health Secretariat of the disease known as "tick fever."

--
Communicated by:
ProMED-PORT
<promed-port@promedmail.org>

[According to data from the Center for Epidemiological Surveillance of the Secretary of Health of Sao Paulo, in the municipality of Piracicaba, in the period between 2002 (the year in which the 1st case was confirmed in the municipality) and 2011, 30 confirmed cases of Brazilian spotted fever were notified; in 2011 there was only one confirmed case (provisional data, as of 11 Jul 2011; source: http://www.cve.saude.sp.gov.br/htm/zoo/fm_lpi.htm). - Mod.RNA]

[The Rocky Mountain spotted fever rickettsia, _R. rickettsii_, is the cause of this illness, which is also referred to as febre maculosa, Sao Paulo exanthematic typhus, Minas Gerais exanthematic typhus, and Brazilian spotted fever.

The organism, which is tickborne, is distributed through much of the USA including the Rocky Mountains and also in parts of southern Canada, Central, and South America.

A HealthMap/ProMED-mail interactive map of Brazil and Sao Paulo state can be seen at http://healthmap.org/r/3Ab5. - Mod.LL]
